1. .bazelversion
This ensures everyone on your team uses the exact same Bazel version. 
text
7.4.0
Use code with caution.

2. MODULE.bazel
This file replaces the old WORKSPACE and manages your external dependencies like rules_python. 
python
module(
    name = "my_python_project",
    version = "1.0.0",
)

# Pull in the official Python rules
bazel_dep(name = "rules_python", version = "0.31.0")

# Configure the Python toolchain (e.g., version 3.11)
python = use_extension("@rules_python//python/extensions:python.bzl", "python")
python.toolchain(
    python_version = "3.11",
    is_default = True,
)
Use code with caution.

3. BUILD.bazel
This file defines your build targets. 
python
load("@rules_python//python:defs.bzl", "py_binary")

py_binary(
    name = "main",
    srcs = ["main.py"],
    main = "main.py",
)
Use code with caution.

4. main.py
Your actual Python logic. 
python
import sys

def run():
    print(f"Success! Running on Python {sys.version}")

if __name__ == "__main__":
    run()
Use code with caution.

How to use it:
Install Bazelisk: It automatically reads your .bazelversion and downloads the right binary.
Build: Run bazel build //:main in your terminal.
Execute: Run bazel run //:main to see your output. 